# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: pydantic-validation
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:pydantic-validation/concepts-models] One of the primary ways of defining schema in Pydantic is via models.
[src:pydantic-validation/concepts-models] Models are simply classes which inherit from `BaseModel` and define fields as annotated attributes.
[src:pydantic-validation/concepts-models] You can think of models as similar to structs in languages like C, or as the requirements of a single endpoint in an API.
[src:pydantic-validation/concepts-models] Models share many similarities with Python’s dataclasses, but have been designed with some subtle-yet-important differences that streamline certain workflows related to validation, serialization, and JSON schema generation.
[src:pydantic-validation/concepts-models] You can find more discussion of this in the Dataclasses section of the docs.
[src:pydantic-validation/concepts-models] Untrusted data can be passed to a model and, after parsing and validation, Pydantic guarantees that the fields of the resultant model instance will conform to the field types defined on the model.
[src:pydantic-validation/concepts-models] Pydantic models support a variety of configuration values (see here for the available configuration values).
[src:pydantic-validation/concepts-models] The documentation on types expands on the supported types.
[src:pydantic-validation/concepts-models] Fields can be customized in a number of ways using the `Field()` function.
[src:pydantic-validation/concepts-models] See the documentation on fields for more information.
[src:pydantic-validation/concepts-models] Initialization of the object will perform all parsing and validation.
[src:pydantic-validation/concepts-models] If no `ValidationError` exception is raised, you know the resulting model instance is valid.
[src:pydantic-validation/concepts-models] `name` wasn't set when `user` was initialized, so the default value was used.
[src:pydantic-validation/concepts-models] The `model_fields_set` attribute can be inspected to check the field names explicitly set during instantiation.
[src:pydantic-validation/concepts-models] Note that the string `'123'` was coerced to an integer and its value is `123`.
[src:pydantic-validation/concepts-models] More details on Pydantic's coercion logic can be found in the data conversion section.
[src:pydantic-validation/concepts-models] Calling dict on the instance will also provide a dictionary, but nested fields will not be recursively converted into dictionaries.
[src:pydantic-validation/concepts-models] `model_dump()` also provides numerous arguments to customize the serialization result.
[src:pydantic-validation/concepts-models] The example above only shows the tip of the iceberg of what models can do.
[src:pydantic-validation/concepts-models] Pydantic may cast input data to force it to conform to model field types, and in some cases this may result in a loss of information.
[src:pydantic-validation/concepts-models] This is a deliberate decision of Pydantic, and is frequently the most useful approach.
[src:pydantic-validation/concepts-models] See this issue for a longer discussion on the subject.
[src:pydantic-validation/concepts-models] Nevertheless, Pydantic provides a strict mode, where no data conversion is performed.
[src:pydantic-validation/concepts-models] Values must be of the same type as the declared field type.
[src:pydantic-validation/concepts-models] In this case, you might be tempted to use the abstract `Sequence` type to allow both lists and tuples.
[src:pydantic-validation/concepts-models] But Pydantic takes care of converting the tuple input to a list, so in most cases this isn't necessary.
[src:pydantic-validation/concepts-models] Besides, using these abstract types can also lead to poor validation performance, and in general using concrete container types will avoid unnecessary checks.
[src:pydantic-validation/concepts-models] If `extra` was set to `'forbid'`, this would fail.
[src:pydantic-validation/concepts-models] `model_validate()`) have an optional `extra` argument that will override the `extra` configuration value of the model for that validation call.
[src:pydantic-validation/concepts-models] For more details, refer to the `extra` API documentation.
[src:pydantic-validation/concepts-models] Pydantic dataclasses also support extra data (see the dataclass configuration section).
[src:pydantic-validation/concepts-models] More complex hierarchical data structures can be defined using models themselves as types in annotations.
[src:pydantic-validation/concepts-models] For more details, see the documentation related to forward annotations.
[src:pydantic-validation/concepts-models] When you define a model class in your code, Pydantic will analyze the body of the class to collect a variety of information required to perform validation and serialization, gathered in a core schema.
[src:pydantic-validation/concepts-models] Notably, the model’s type annotations are evaluated to understand the valid types for each field (more information can be found in the Architecture documentation).
[src:pydantic-validation/concepts-models] However, it might be the case that annotations refer to symbols not defined when the model class is being created.
[src:pydantic-validation/concepts-models] `Bar` is not yet defined when the `Foo` class is being created.
[src:pydantic-validation/concepts-models] For this reason, a forward annotation is being used.
[src:pydantic-validation/concepts-models] Pydantic tries to determine when this is necessary automatically and error if it wasn’t done, but you may want to call `model_rebuild()` proactively when dealing with recursive models or generics.
[src:pydantic-validation/concepts-models] In V2, `model_rebuild()` replaced `update_forward_refs()` from V1.
[src:pydantic-validation/concepts-models] There are some slight differences with the new behavior.
[src:pydantic-validation/concepts-models] The biggest change is that when calling `model_rebuild()` on the outermost model, it builds a core schema used for validation of the whole model (nested models and all), so all types at all levels need to be ready before `model_rebuild()` is called.
[src:pydantic-validation/concepts-models] Pydantic can validate data in three different modes: *Python*, *JSON* and *strings*.
[src:pydantic-validation/concepts-models] Compared to using the model constructor, it is possible to control several validation parameters when using the `model_validate_*()` methods (strictness, extra data, validation context, etc.).
[src:pydantic-validation/concepts-models] Pydantic also provides the `model_construct()` method, which allows models to be created **without validation**.
[src:pydantic-validation/concepts-models] Note that for root models, the root value can be passed to `model_construct()` positionally, instead of using a keyword argument.
[src:pydantic-validation/concepts-models] Pydantic provides a default `__init__()` implementation for Pydantic models, that is called *only* when using the model constructor (and not with the `model_validate_*()` methods).
[src:pydantic-validation/concepts-models] This implementation delegates validation to `pydantic-core`.
[src:pydantic-validation/concepts-models] However, it is possible to define a custom `__init__()` on your models.
[src:pydantic-validation/concepts-models] In this case, it will be called unconditionally from all the validation methods, without performing validation (and so you should call `super().__init__(**kwargs)` in your implementation).
[src:pydantic-validation/concepts-models] Defining a custom `__init__()` is not recommended, as all the validation parameters (strictness, extra data behavior, validation context) will be lost.
[src:pydantic-validation/concepts-models] Pydantic will raise a `ValidationError` exception whenever it finds an error in the data it’s validating.
[src:pydantic-validation/concepts-models] A single exception will be raised regardless of the number of errors found, and that validation error will contain information about all of the errors and how they happened.
[src:pydantic-validation/concepts-models] See Error Handling for details on standard and custom errors.
[src:pydantic-validation/concepts-models] (Formerly known as “ORM Mode”/`from_orm()`).
[src:pydantic-validation/concepts-models] When using the `model_validate()` method, Pydantic can also validate arbitrary objects, by getting attributes on the object corresponding the field names.
[src:pydantic-validation/concepts-models] One common application of this functionality is integration with object-relational mappings (ORMs).
[src:pydantic-validation/concepts-models] This feature need to be manually enabled, either by setting the `from_attributes` configuration value, or by using the `from_attributes` parameter on `model_validate()`.
[src:pydantic-validation/concepts-models] The example here uses SQLAlchemy, but the same approach should work for any ORM.
[src:pydantic-validation/concepts-models] When using attributes to validate models, model instances will be created from both top-level attributes and deeper-nested attributes as appropriate.
[src:pydantic-validation/concepts-models] The `model_copy()` method allows models to be duplicated (with optional updates), which is particularly useful when working with frozen models.
[src:pydantic-validation/concepts-models] Pydantic supports the creation of generic models to make it easier to reuse a common model structure.
[src:pydantic-validation/concepts-models] Both the new type parameter syntax (introduced by PEP 695 in Python 3.12) and the old syntax are supported (refer to the Python documentation for more details).
[src:pydantic-validation/concepts-models] Declare one or more type variables to use to parameterize your model.
[src:pydantic-validation/concepts-models] Declare a Pydantic model that inherits from `BaseModel` and `typing.Generic` (in this specific order), and add the list of type variables you declared previously as parameters to the `Generic` parent.
[src:pydantic-validation/concepts-models] Use the type variables as annotations where you will want to replace them with other types.
[src:pydantic-validation/concepts-models] Declare a Pydantic model and add the list of type variables as type parameters.
[src:pydantic-validation/concepts-models] Full support for the type parameter syntax and type variable defaults.
[src:pydantic-validation/concepts-models] Any configuration, validation or serialization logic set on the generic model will also be applied to the parametrized classes, in the same way as when inheriting from a model class.
[src:pydantic-validation/concepts-models] Any custom methods or attributes will also be inherited.
[src:pydantic-validation/concepts-models] Generic models also integrate properly with type checkers, so you get all the type checking you would expect if you were to declare a distinct type for each parametrization.
[src:pydantic-validation/concepts-models] The `OuterT` model is parametrized with `int`, but the data associated with the `T` annotations during validation is of type `str`, leading to validation errors.
[src:pydantic-validation/concepts-models] When using nested generic models, Pydantic sometimes performs revalidation in an attempt to produce the most intuitive validation result.
[src:pydantic-validation/concepts-models] This adds some validation overhead, but makes things more intuitive for cases like that shown below.
[src:pydantic-validation/concepts-models] Note, validation will still fail if you, for example are validating against `GenericModel[int]` and pass in an instance `GenericModel[str](a='not an int')`.
[src:pydantic-validation/concepts-models] It’s also worth noting that this pattern will re-trigger any custom validation as well, like additional model validators and the like.
[src:pydantic-validation/concepts-models] Validators will be called once on the first pass, validating directly against `GenericModel[Any]`.
[src:pydantic-validation/concepts-models] That validation fails, as `GenericModel[int]` is not a subclass of `GenericModel[Any]`.
[src:pydantic-validation/concepts-models] This relates to the warning above about the complications of using parametrized generics in `isinstance()` and `issubclass()` checks.
[src:pydantic-validation/concepts-models] Then, the validators will be called again on the second pass, during more lax force-revalidation phase, which succeeds.
[src:pydantic-validation/concepts-models] When the generic isn't parametrized, the input data is validated against the `ItemT` upper bound.
[src:pydantic-validation/concepts-models] Given that `ItemBase` has no fields, the `item` field information is lost.
[src:pydantic-validation/concepts-models] In this case, the type variable is explicitly parametrized, so the input data is validated against the `IntItem` class.
[src:pydantic-validation/concepts-models] However, if constraints or a default value (as per PEP 696) is being used, then the default type or constraints will be used for both validation and serialization if the type variable is not parametrized.
[src:pydantic-validation/concepts-models] There are some occasions where it is desirable to create a model using runtime information to specify the fields.
[src:pydantic-validation/concepts-models] When providing a single element for field definitions, any type can be used (previously, only an `Annotated` form could be provided).
[src:pydantic-validation/concepts-models] The special keyword arguments `__config__` and `__base__` can be used to customize the new model.
[src:pydantic-validation/concepts-models] This includes extending a base model with extra fields.
[src:pydantic-validation/concepts-models] You can also add validators by passing a dictionary to the `__validators__` argument.
[src:pydantic-validation/concepts-models] Make sure that the validators names do not clash with any of the field names as internally, Pydantic gathers all members into a namespace and mimics the normal creation of a class using the `types` module utilities.
[src:pydantic-validation/concepts-models] See also: the dynamic model example, providing guidelines to derive an optional model from another one.
[src:pydantic-validation/concepts-models] Pydantic models can be defined with a “custom root type” by subclassing `pydantic.RootModel`.
[src:pydantic-validation/concepts-models] The root type can be any type supported by Pydantic, and is specified by the generic parameter to `RootModel`.
[src:pydantic-validation/concepts-models] The root value can be passed to the model `__init__` or `model_validate` via the first and only argument.
[src:pydantic-validation/concepts-models] If you want to access items in the `root` field directly or to iterate over the items, you can implement custom `__iter__` and `__getitem__` functions, as shown in the following example.
[src:pydantic-validation/concepts-models] Models can be configured to be immutable via `model_config['frozen'] = True`.
[src:pydantic-validation/concepts-models] When this is set, attempting to change the values of instance attributes will raise errors.
[src:pydantic-validation/concepts-models] Trying to change `a` caused an error, and `a` remains unchanged.
[src:pydantic-validation/concepts-models] However, the dict `b` is mutable, and the immutability of `foobar` doesn’t stop `b` from being changed.
[src:pydantic-validation/concepts-models] Pydantic models can be used alongside Python’s Abstract Base Classes (ABCs).
[src:pydantic-validation/concepts-models] Attributes whose name has a leading underscore are not treated as fields by Pydantic, and are not included in the model schema.
[src:pydantic-validation/concepts-models] Instead, these are converted into a “private attribute” which is not validated or even set during calls to `__init__`, `model_validate`, etc.
[src:pydantic-validation/concepts-models] Private attribute names must start with underscore to prevent conflicts with model fields.
[src:pydantic-validation/concepts-models] However, dunder names (such as `__attr__`) are not supported, and will be completely ignored from the model definition.
[src:pydantic-validation/concepts-models] Default factories can take the validated model data as an argument.
[src:pydantic-validation/concepts-models] An accurate signature is useful for introspection purposes and libraries like `FastAPI` or `hypothesis`.
[src:pydantic-validation/concepts-models] To be included in the signature, a field’s alias or name must be a valid Python identifier.
[src:pydantic-validation/concepts-models] Pydantic will prioritize a field’s alias over its name when generating the signature, but may use the field name if the alias is not a valid Python identifier.
[src:pydantic-validation/concepts-models] If a field’s alias and name are *both* not valid identifiers (which may be possible through exotic use of `create_model`), a `**data` argument will be added.
[src:pydantic-validation/concepts-models] In addition, the `**data` argument will always be present in the signature if `model_config['extra'] == 'allow'`.
[src:pydantic-validation/concepts-models] Pydantic supports structural pattern matching for models, as introduced by PEP 636 in Python 3.10.
[src:pydantic-validation/concepts-models] In many cases, arguments passed to the constructor will be copied in order to perform validation and, where necessary, coercion.
[src:pydantic-validation/concepts-validators] In addition to Pydantic’s built-in validation capabilities, you can leverage custom validators at the field and model levels to enforce more complex constraints and ensure the integrity of your data.
[src:pydantic-validation/concepts-validators] In its simplest form, a field validator is a callable taking the value to be validated as an argument and **returning the validated value**.
[src:pydantic-validation/concepts-validators] The callable can perform checks for specific conditions (see raising validation errors) and make changes to the validated value (coercion or mutation).
[src:pydantic-validation/concepts-validators] Here is an example of a validator performing a validation check, and returning the value unchanged.
[src:pydantic-validation/concepts-validators] Note that it is important to return the validated value.
[src:pydantic-validation/concepts-validators] Here is an example of a validator performing a validation check, and returning the value unchanged, this time using the `field_validator()` decorator.
[src:pydantic-validation/concepts-validators] `'after'` is the default mode for the decorator, and can be omitted.
[src:pydantic-validation/concepts-validators] Here is an example of a validator making changes to the validated value (no exception is raised).
[src:pydantic-validation/concepts-validators] Notice the use of `Any` as a type hint for `value`.
[src:pydantic-validation/concepts-validators] *Before* validators take the raw input, which can be anything.
[src:pydantic-validation/concepts-validators] Note that you might want to check for other sequence types (such as tuples) that would normally successfully validate against the `list` type.
[src:pydantic-validation/concepts-validators] *Before* validators give you more flexibility, but you have to account for every possible case.
[src:pydantic-validation/concepts-validators] Pydantic still performs validation against the `int` type, no matter if our `ensure_list` validator did operations on the original input type.
[src:pydantic-validation/concepts-validators] Although `'invalid'` shouldn't validate against the `int` type, Pydantic accepts the input.
[src:pydantic-validation/concepts-validators] While both approaches can achieve the same thing, each pattern provides different benefits.
[src:pydantic-validation/concepts-validators] As mentioned in the annotated pattern documentation, we can also make use of validators for specific parts of the annotation (in this case, validation is applied for list items, but not the whole list).
[src:pydantic-validation/concepts-validators] It is also easier to understand which validators are applied to a type, by just looking at the field annotation.
[src:pydantic-validation/concepts-validators] Validation can also be performed on the entire model’s data using the `model_validator()` decorator.
[src:pydantic-validation/concepts-validators] Notice the use of `Any` as a type hint for `data`.
[src:pydantic-validation/concepts-validators] Most of the time, the input data will be a dictionary (e.g. when calling `UserModel(username='...')`).
[src:pydantic-validation/concepts-validators] For instance, if the `from_attributes` configuration value is set, you might receive an arbitrary class instance for the `data` argument.
[src:pydantic-validation/concepts-validators] For field validators, the already validated data can be accessed using the `data` property.
[src:pydantic-validation/concepts-validators] The `data` property is `None` for model validators.
[src:pydantic-validation/concepts-validators] Similarly, you can use a context for serialization.
[src:pydantic-validation/concepts-validators] It is currently not possible to provide a context when directly instantiating a model (i.e. when calling `Model(...)`).
[src:pydantic-validation/concepts-validators] Internally, validators defined using the decorator are converted to their annotated form counterpart and added last after the existing metadata for the field.
[src:pydantic-validation/concepts-validators] This means that the same ordering logic applies.
[src:pydantic-validation/concepts-validators] Pydantic provides a few special utilities that can be used to customize validation.
[src:pydantic-validation/concepts-validators] Note that the validation of the second item is skipped.
[src:pydantic-validation/concepts-validators] If it has the wrong type it will emit a warning during serialization.
[src:pydantic-validation/concepts-validators] When using *before*, *plain* or *wrap* field validators, the accepted input type may be different from the field annotation.
[src:pydantic-validation/concepts-validators] While the type hint for `value` is `str`, the `cast_ints` validator also allows integers.
[src:pydantic-validation/concepts-validators] As a convenience, Pydantic will use the field type if the argument is not provided (unless you are using a *plain* validator, in which case `json_schema_input_type` defaults to `Any` as the field type is completely discarded).
[src:pydantic-validation/data-type] In computer science and computer programming, a **data type** (or simply **type**) is a collection or grouping of data values, usually specified by a set of possible values, a set of allowed operations on these values, and/or a representation of these values as machine types.
[src:pydantic-validation/data-type] A data type specification in a program constrains the possible values that an expression, such as a variable or a function call, might take.
[src:pydantic-validation/data-type] On literal data, it tells the compiler or interpreter how the programmer intends to use the data.
[src:pydantic-validation/data-type] Most programming languages support basic data types of integer numbers (of varying sizes), floating-point numbers (which approximate real numbers), characters and Booleans.
[src:pydantic-validation/data-type] A data type may be specified for many reasons: similarity, convenience, or to focus the attention.
[src:pydantic-validation/data-type] It is frequently a matter of good organization that aids the understanding of complex definitions.
[src:pydantic-validation/data-type] Almost all programming languages explicitly include the notion of data type, though the possible data types are often restricted by considerations of simplicity, computability, or regularity.
[src:pydantic-validation/data-type] An explicit data type declaration typically allows the compiler to choose an efficient machine representation, but the conceptual organization offered by data types should not be discounted.
[src:pydantic-validation/data-type] Different languages may use different data types or similar types with different semantics.
[src:pydantic-validation/data-type] For example, in the Python programming language, `int` represents an arbitrary-precision integer which has the traditional numeric operations such as addition, subtraction, and multiplication.
[src:pydantic-validation/data-type] However, in the Java programming language, the type `int` represents the set of 32-bit integers ranging in value from −2,147,483,648 to 2,147,483,647, with arithmetic operations that wrap on overflow.
[src:pydantic-validation/data-type] In Rust this 32-bit integer type is denoted `i32` and panics on overflow in debug mode.
[src:pydantic-validation/data-type] Most programming languages also allow the programmer to define additional data types, usually by combining multiple elements of other types and defining the valid operations of the new data type.
[src:pydantic-validation/data-type] For example, a programmer might create a new data type named "complex number" that would include real and imaginary parts, or a color data type represented by three bytes denoting the amounts each of red, green, and blue, and a string representing the color's name.
[src:pydantic-validation/data-type] Data types are used within type systems, which offer various ways of defining, implementing, and using them.
[src:pydantic-validation/data-type] In a type system, a data type represents a constraint placed upon the interpretation of data, describing representation, interpretation and structure of values or objects stored in computer memory.
[src:pydantic-validation/data-type] The type system uses data type information to check correctness of computer programs that access or manipulate the data.
[src:pydantic-validation/data-type] A compiler may use the static type of a value to optimize the storage it needs and the choice of algorithms for operations on the value.
[src:pydantic-validation/data-type] In many C compilers the `float` data type, for example, is represented in 32 bits, in accord with the IEEE specification for single-precision floating point numbers.
[src:pydantic-validation/data-type] They will thus use floating-point-specific microprocessor operations on those values (floating-point addition, multiplication, etc.).
[src:pydantic-validation/data-type] , such definitions provide no intuitive meaning of the types.
[src:pydantic-validation/data-type] A type is defined in terms of a composition of more primitive types—often machine types.
[src:pydantic-validation/data-type] A type is a set of possible values which a variable can possess.
[src:pydantic-validation/data-type] The definition in terms of a representation was often done in imperative languages such as ALGOL and Pascal, while the definition in terms of a value space and behaviour was used in higher-level languages such as Simula and CLU.
[src:pydantic-validation/data-type] Types including behavior align more closely with object-oriented models, whereas a structured programming model would tend to not include code, and are called plain old data structures.
[src:pydantic-validation/data-type] The terminology varies - in the literature, primitive, built-in, basic, atomic, and fundamental may be used interchangeably.
[src:pydantic-validation/data-type] All data in computers based on digital electronics is represented as bits (alternatives 0 and 1) on the lowest level.
[src:pydantic-validation/data-type] The smallest addressable unit of data is usually a group of bits called a byte (usually an octet, which is 8 bits).
[src:pydantic-validation/data-type] The unit processed by machine code instructions is called a word (as of 2026, typically 32/64 bits).
[src:pydantic-validation/data-type] Machine data types *expose* or make available fine-grained control over hardware, but this can also expose implementation details that make code less portable.
[src:pydantic-validation/data-type] Hence machine types are mainly used in systems programming or low-level programming languages.
[src:pydantic-validation/data-type] In higher-level languages most data types are *abstracted* in that they do not have a language-defined machine representation.
[src:pydantic-validation/data-type] The C programming language, for instance, supplies types such as Booleans, integers, floating-point numbers, etc., but the precise bit representations of these types are implementation-defined.
[src:pydantic-validation/data-type] The only C type with a precise machine representation is the `char` type that represents a byte.
[src:pydantic-validation/data-type] The Boolean type represents the values true and false.
[src:pydantic-validation/data-type] Although only two values are possible, they are more often represented as a byte or word rather as a single bit as it requires more machine instructions to store and retrieve an individual bit.
[src:pydantic-validation/data-type] Many programming languages do not have an explicit Boolean type, instead using an integer type and interpreting (for instance) 0 as false and other values as true.
[src:pydantic-validation/data-type] Boolean data refers to the logical structure of how the language is interpreted to the machine language.
[src:pydantic-validation/data-type] In this case a Boolean 0 refers to the logic False.
[src:pydantic-validation/data-type] True is always a non zero, especially a one which is known as Boolean 1.
[src:pydantic-validation/data-type] Almost all programming languages supply one or more integer data types.
[src:pydantic-validation/data-type] They may either supply a small number of predefined subtypes restricted to certain ranges (such as `short` and `long` and their corresponding `unsigned` variants in C/C++); or allow users to freely define subranges such as 1..12 (e.g.
[src:pydantic-validation/data-type] If a corresponding native type does not exist on the target platform, the compiler will break them down into code using types that do exist.
[src:pydantic-validation/data-type] For instance, if a 32-bit integer is requested on a 16 bit platform, the compiler will tacitly treat it as an array of two 16 bit integers.
[src:pydantic-validation/data-type] Floating point data types represent certain fractional values (rational numbers, mathematically).
[src:pydantic-validation/data-type] Although they have predefined limits on both their maximum values and their precision, they are sometimes misleadingly called reals (evocative of mathematical real numbers).
[src:pydantic-validation/data-type] They are typically stored internally in the form a × 2b (where a and b are integers), but displayed in familiar decimal form.
[src:pydantic-validation/data-type] Fixed point data types are convenient for representing monetary values.
[src:pydantic-validation/data-type] They are often implemented internally as integers, leading to predefined limits.
[src:pydantic-validation/data-type] For independence from architecture details, a Bignum or arbitrary precision `numeric` type might be supplied.
[src:pydantic-validation/data-type] This represents an integer or rational to a precision limited only by the available memory and computational resources on the system.
[src:pydantic-validation/data-type] Bignum implementations of arithmetic operations on machine-sized values are significantly slower than the corresponding machine operations.
[src:pydantic-validation/data-type] The enumerated type has distinct values, which can be compared and assigned, but which do not necessarily have any particular concrete representation in the computer's memory; compilers and interpreters can represent them arbitrarily.
[src:pydantic-validation/data-type] For example, the four suits in a deck of playing cards may be four enumerators named *CLUB*, *DIAMOND*, *HEART*, *SPADE*, belonging to an enumerated type named *suit*.
[src:pydantic-validation/data-type] If a variable *V* is declared having *suit* as its data type, one can assign any of those four values to it.
