[src:pydantic-validation/serialization] Generally a Lisp data structure can be serialized with the functions "`read`" and "`print`".
[src:pydantic-validation/serialization] A variable foo containing, for example, a list of arrays would be printed by `(print foo)`.
[src:pydantic-validation/serialization] Similarly an object can be read from a stream named s by `(read s)`.
[src:pydantic-validation/serialization] These two parts of the Lisp implementation are called the Printer and the Reader.
[src:pydantic-validation/serialization] The output of "`print`" is human readable; it uses lists demarked by parentheses, for example: `(4 2.9 "x" y)`.
[src:pydantic-validation/serialization] In many types of Lisp, including Common Lisp, the printer cannot represent every type of data because it is not clear how to do so.
[src:pydantic-validation/serialization] In Common Lisp for example the printer cannot print CLOS objects.
[src:pydantic-validation/serialization] Instead the programmer may write a method on the generic function `print-object`, this will be invoked when the object is printed.
[src:pydantic-validation/serialization] This is somewhat similar to the method used in Ruby.
[src:pydantic-validation/serialization] Lisp code itself is written in the syntax of the reader, called read syntax.
[src:pydantic-validation/serialization] Most languages use separate and different parsers to deal with code and data, Lisp only uses one.
[src:pydantic-validation/serialization] A file containing lisp code may be read into memory as a data structure, transformed by another program, then possibly executed or written out, such as in a read–eval–print loop.
[src:pydantic-validation/serialization] Not all readers/writers support cyclic, recursive or shared structures.
